causation.

=== Russell's argument from contiguity ===
In [[local:zz.texts/russell1917-mysticismAndLogic.pdf|_On the Notion of Cause_]] Russell claims that causes must be temporally
contiguous with their effects. For if they are not, then there is some interval
between causes and effects and <q>However short we make the interval, something
may happen during this interval which prevents the expected result.</q>

Hence the cause in question does not <q>necessitate</q> its effects and is
therefore not the 'total' cause (i.e. it does not completely determine the
effect). But if time is continuous then no two moments in time are contiguous.
For any two instants in the same continuous time stream (in special relativity
this would be a set of space-time points that are simultaneous from some
inertial reference frame) there is a determinate time interval between them. If
that interval is 0 seconds then the two instants are identical. If the interval
between them is not 0 seconds then, since time is continuous, it contains an
infinite number of instants, and hence the original two instants are not
contiguous.

If we add that no causal influence can propagate faster than a fixed speed (such
as the speed of light) then action at a distance is prohibited, and much the
same argument applies to spatial contiguity.

Of course time _intervals_ may still be contiguous, provided one is an open and
the other a closed set of time instants (at the boundary between them). For
instance the set of instants _t_ such that 1:59am<=_t_<=2am and the set of instants
such that 2am<_t_<=2:01am are contiguous. But Russell notes that it is <q>too
strange to be accepted, in spite of bare logical possibility â€” that the cause,
