Consider the sphere(:or N-dimensional hypersphere, if we are considering a space of N dimensions rather than just 3:) of points in space and time which are _T_ time units
prior to a given point _P_, and less than or equal to _T_ times the maximum
speed of causal propagation space units away from _P_. (In special relativity
this will be the intersection of a set of simultaneous(:from some perspective:) space-time points
and _P's_ past light cone.) Nothing can come from outside this sphere to
<q>prevent the expected result</q> and hence the properties of the points in
that sphere may well necessitate the properties of the point _P_. If the system
obeys a principle of sufficient reason (i.e. nothing happens without a cause and
causes completely determine their effects) then the state of the objects in that
sphere completely determines the state of/at _P_. (For nothing outside that
sphere can have any casual influence of _P_ and by hypothesis the state of _P_
is completely causally determined.) Even if the causal laws are indeterministic
then the probability distribution over the range of _P's_ potential properties
(or whatever it is about _P_ that is causally determined) is casually determined
by the state of things in the relevant sphere. (Though there is a caveat here
which we will discuss when we return to indeterministic causation below.)

